                | Final Checkpoint&colon;
                span.text-muted Launching and finishing up
              p.lead
                | Now if you open the gallery page&comma; everything&apos;s empty because we haven&apos;t accessed the facebook page&period;  Head over to &quot;yourapp&period;herokuapp&period;com&sol;auth&sol;facebook&quot;&comma; this should start the process to request the information from facebook&period;  If you have less than 1000 photos of yourself&comma; this shouldn&apos;t take longer than a minute&period;
              p.lead
                | Now if you go to your &quot;&sol;gallery&quot; page&comma; everything should be loaded up and ready to go&period;  There&apos;s still so much that you can add to your personal site&comma; including a dashboard of your own&period;  This is extremely important because editting your &quot;Jade&quot; pages is a pain&comma; it would be much easier if the Jade page simply read from a MongoDB instance and placed that on the page&period;  There are plenty examples of Node-based blogs&comma; such as
                a(href='http://cwbuecheler.com/web/tutorials/2013/node-express-mongo/')  this
              p.lead
                | Furthermore&comma; it&apos;s much more impressive to scale up the number of &quot;dynos&sol;processes&quot; your application is built on if you expand to something larger&period;  1 Dyno really isn&apos;t impressive and your web application doesn&apos;t actually run very fast&period;  If you get many page hits&comma; what you&apos;ll end up getting is a very large problem with latency issues&period;  But now it&apos;s all up to you on how you want to customize your site&excl; Feel free to email me if you liked this tutorial or want to tell me how this can be improved&excl;
